Many people ask me what it is like having a twin sister. Some things I really enjoy about having a twin is you can't call the other person ugly in an argument:) Also, you can get the other twin to try on your clothes to see what it looks like from behind. Some things that I don't like about having a twin is that it is a lot harder to have your own separate identity. We have to share a lot of the same things like clothes, and we celebrate our birthday on the same day, so we have to share presents. It is hard because people always compare us. I always try not to compare myself, because it always lowers my self-esteem, especially because my sister is better than me at certain things. But, when I constantly hear it from other people, it is hard to ignore. We always have to stand back to back to see who is taller. We try hard to have our own separate identities. For example, I cut my hair so it is shorter than my sisters hair, and she had gotten bangs last year. Even though having a twin is hard, I love my sister no matter what.

Dear Michael Monroe,

I am a teacher, researcher and writer in Japan. I write regularly for Digital Mobile Language Learning <digitalmobilelanguagelearning.org> and featured PenPalSchools in a piece earlier this year. I also conducted a research project measuring intercultural development among Japanese learners who participated in a six-week exchange using PenPalSchools which was published in The Center for ELF Journal, 1(1). I am using it again this term with students from another university class.

I really like the upgrades which are taking place to this program. When I used it last fall, the biggest problem was the lack of participation by the American high school counterparts our class was paired with. It seems that in this latest iteration, only those who actually write at least one response are goint to be paired. This is much better. I also am happy to see that news outside of America is now being included, as that was another problem I noticed in the previous iteration. 

I have a few suggestions for the next iteration. 

1. Consider not limit the parings to a class-class pairing, but allow for a more free pairing of pen pals. In the case of Japan, class sizes are usually around 30-40. In other countries in Asia, often larger. Last fall one of my classes was paired with a much smaller class, and there ended up being two or more Japanese students paired with each foreign student. 

2. In week-six, there is a rather goofy image and an "ask an adult" prompt. While I understand this may be appealing to very small children, I think this may be insulting to our university participants here in Japan. In addition, the pedagogy is lost on me when the opportunity for engaging with the pen pal seems much more relevant than interviewing a native of your own country and reporting on it back to your pen pal. Perhaps the pen pals could use this opportunity to ask questions of each other? This seems a more appropriate prompt. 

3. Consider having pen pal exchanges between different English as a Lingua Franca (ELF) learners. I do not know how many international participants you have yet, but there are more ELF speakers in the world than native English speakers. If finding active U.S. participants is a problem, perhaps a shift in the direction of an international focus for this forum would better facilitate the goals of intercultural development worldwide. As an example, Japanese ELF users could be paired with ELF users in Italy. In the future I hope that the program will develop enough that this may be possible. 

Thank you for taking the time to read this, and I wish you the best with the PenPalSchools program. 

Sincerely, 

Simeon Flowers
Jr. Associate Professor
Tokai University
Hiratsuka, Japan
flowers@tokai.ac.jp

I don't mind at all, don't even stress. I guess its good that you don't have that habit, it gives you time to do more useful things. Okay, South Africa has a pretty hectic history as most countries do, but it is the way it is today because of that. I don't want to bore you with a history lesson but I'll quickly touch on important points: The Dutch were the first to colonise `South Africa, I think in 1652, and the British came in the early 1800s and from then it was a tug of war of who owned the colony (not sure if 'owned' is the correct term) Lots of stuff happened, then there was Apartheid. In 1994 the country became a democracy. The reason why the country is so multicultural is because we have people of European descent, Indians migrated in the late 1800s, as well as the original African people that were here in the first place. There is such a diverse group of people because of our history and thats why I love South Africa. Yes, English is very much my first language, although I can also speak a bit of Afrikaans :D Is English your first language? Yeah I'd say I do pretty well in academics, I suck at sport so I make up for it by doing well in school. Thats so great! Which movie was it? Yes the capital is Pretoria, but its a pretty boring place.. Oh and I'm mixed race - my dad is Indian and my mom is White, and my grandfather on my mother's side came here from Sicily a long time ago, where he met my grandma who is Afrikaans - so not really :) I can honestly say I really don't know much about Portugal at all except the fact that Portuguese food is the bomb so I hope you'll enlighten me. Hope to hear from you soon! Sinead x

Hi, Sinead! Please, feel free to share your country's History with me. I love History, so that's not boring at all for me. In fact, if you don't mind, I'll share a bit about the History of Portugal with you. Portugal is a really old nation, that also had it's good share of conflicts (as usual, specially in Europe). The Iberian Peninsula, where I live, has been in the hands of barbaric tribes (such as the Suebi, Visigoths and Lusitanians), the Roman Empire, and even the Arabs, throughout time. 
     In 711, Tarik, a Berber commander, invaded the Iberian Peninsula and quickly conquered the majority of the territory (occupied by the Visigoths, in that time), with the exception of the Asturias region, in the far north. There, the Christian forces regrew, reorganized, and started heading south and reclaiming their lost lands, in a 800 year period that is known as the Reconquista (means the Reconquest, in Portuguese). During that time, several Christian kingdoms were born: Asturias, Navarre, Aragon, Castile, León. In addition, the County of Portucale, a vassal of Kingdom of León, was created. 
     It wouldn't take long before the people of the County aspired to independence, and so it was. In 1143, after a lot of stuff that I'm not going to tell because it would take ages, Portugal was finally recongnized by the Pope as an independent kingdom, with Afonso Henriques as it's king. This guy is pretty much the most badass our History. He was our first King and conquered almost all the territory that corresponds to today's Portugal.
     Our nation's Golden Age came in the XV-XVI centuries, with the Discoveries. We were pioneers in maritime exploration, mostly because of our geographical position. Portugal created colonies all around the world: Brazil in South America; Angola, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, Cape Verde, São Tomé e Principe in Africa; Macau, Goa, Daman and Diu in Asia; East Timor in Oceania. We also discovered the archipelagos of Madeira and the Azores, and we estabilished the first maritime route to India, in 1500, by the navigator Vasco da Gama. In fact, the Portuguese explorer Bartolomeu Dias was the first to cross the Cape of Good Hope, in South Africa. In fact, we named it Cape of Good Hope, such as the greatness of the deed. Oh yes, Portugal was pretty important back in the good old days. Of course, with democracy, today we don't have those colonies anymore. 
     Holy crap, I got lost in my thoughts and wrote a LOT. Sorry! No, English is not my first language, Portuguese is. I saw Johannesburg in a sci-fi movie called District 9, but it was a strange film, so it wasn't really the ideal touristic tour xD
     What exactly is Afrikaans? Oh, and by the way, it must be interesting to have such a multicultural family. I wrote so much in this message that I should probably save up something for the next letters, so bye. I hope to hear from you soon! Antonio

Hi, Sinead! Well, I really only spend time with my friends during school, because I usually go to the Azores for the whole summer or most of it. In fact, I am in the Azores right now, I traveled here yesterday. In case you don't know, the Azores is an archipelago that belongs to Portugal. It's a group of nine islands in the middle of the Atlantic Ocean, halfway between North America and Europe. I have family here, so I try to come here every summer, and I love it. Right now, I'm in Terceira island, but I'm flying to São Jorge island this afternoon. Regarding school life, it's pretty much the usual boring routine. School starts at 8.20 in the morning and, depending on the day, it may end at 4.40 or 1.30 in the afternoon. I also have orienteering at school so, on Mondays, I only go home at 8.00 in the evening. It's the most tiring day of the week for me, or it was, since the schedule is going to change this year. My school is kind of old, so it isn't in the best shape, but as long as I can learn there, what is the problem? What else? I chose the Science/Technology path, so my classes include Biology, Geology, Physics, Chemistry, English, Philosophy, P.E and Portuguese, of course. My favorite classes are definitely Physics and Geology, but I also enjoy Biology. What about you? I'm really looking forward for 11th grade, because my school is involved in an exchanging program with other European countries, so I might have the chance to travel to Germany, Finland or even Iceland. The project is called "Water Around Us". Have you traveled much? I hope to hear from you soon! Antonio

English, Afrikaans, LO and maths are all compulsory though. I love all my subjects equally, they're such a fitting combination for me. We also have exchange but we can do it in grade 10, some of my friends went to Germany, Australia, India and America. I've been to Singapore, Australia, New Zealand, Thailand and Mauritius. Hi, Sinead! Still in school??!! When is your summer holiday? Anyways, orienteering is a really cool sport, although it's not very known. It's basically a navigation game, but we have to do it in the minimum time possible. We are given a compass and a map with several points marked on it, and we must find them using only our navigational skills. On each point, there is a sensor where we check in with a chip we take in our hands. It's an amazing activity, specially if you like being outdoors, because competition usually takes place in areas like forests, parks or mountains. This sport is particularly famous in Nordic countries, I think. It's so cool that you get to chose any combination. It's impossible to have both History and Science classes here. They're in different "categories", if you know what I mean. Wow, you get to travel so much in your school! What was your favorite journey? I'm going back home on the 9th of September, just before school starts. Oh, by the way, don't worry if I take too long to reply, because I travel a lot around the islands, and sometimes I don't have much time to get in the computer. I was in the island of Pico on the last three days, I only came back to São Jorge island today, on a small boat. São Jorge is like my holidays headquarters xD, where I keep all my stuff (including the computer). And no, your memory does not deceive you, Eragon is one of the volumes in the collection. Hi Jonah,
Just imagine I will dance waltz! In Hungary there are three schools in your life. The primary school is that school, you are in from ages 6-14 (When you are in age 6-7 you are in class 1st when you are in 7-8 you are in class 2nd, when you are in age 8-9 you are in class 3rd… etc. Until the 8th class, because you start the next year in the secondary school.). That is the first school of a Hungarian child’s life. The second is the secondary school, you are here from 14-18 years. When you are over 18, you can learn in a university.
Now, I am in class 8th, which is the last class of the primary school, and I’m 13 years old now. And when adolescents (or teenagers?) are in class 8th, they dance waltz. This is a Hungarian tradition, and I don’t know whether you know what waltz like, so I write it down. This is dance in triple time performed by a couple who as a pair turn rhythmically around and around as they progress around the dance floor. I hope you understand it. 
And you wrote, that you’re home schooled. It sounds interesting and great! Do you like it? I would like to try it once! My favourite subjects are P.E (I like sports and running) History (I like learn about my and the other countries) I like English (I don’t explain why, because it will be longer than the page :)) and Literature (I like poets, humor, and poems). In my free time I always reading fantasy, and sci-fi books or trying to sing, but I can’t sing so beautiful.
Hungarians got a game, called ‘Mit vinnél egy lakatlan szigetre? ’ --> this is the Hungarian name of the game. (What things do you bring to an uninhabited island?) You have to list 3 things.
I wrote about singing for you, so I won’t tell Hungarian words, I will tell a Hungarian poem:
A börtön ablakába sohasem süt be a Nap,
Ragyogón süt a Nap,
És szikrázik az ég,
Csak a szívem szomorú, ha rád gondolok én
Szeretlek én…
This is a Hungarian poem about a man, who is in a prison. I translate into English for you:
The prison window into the sun never shines,
The sun is shining brightly,
And sparkle in the sky,
Only my heart was sad when I think of you
I love you…
Best regards,
Regi

I'm sure it's nice having older siblings to help along the way.
Where I live in North Carolina, it is very rural.  There are farms and lots of mini cities in the middle of nowhere.  It's hard to predict the weather here, but it's normally very hot in summer and very cold in winter.  There are also hurricanes sometimes, but they rarely reach N.C.  
Towards the coast there are famous beaches, lighthouses, and the Outer Banks around the state's shoreline.  There are also lots of shipwreck and pirate artifacts at the beaches from the colonial days, as well as battlefield sites.  There are many festivals that take place in the mountains, and many people visit in the fall to look at the leaves.
I don't know much about Iowa, but I'm looking forward to learning more!  I looked up pictures of Okoboji, and it's really pretty.  I hadn't known it existed until now.

I think Belize is a good country for those who want a relaxed life and those who are retired.
